        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
                <p>J. Judelsohn&#44;<lb/>
                510 South Fifth Street.<lb/>
                P.O. Box 476&#44; Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            <p>Sept 25&#47;84<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>City<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>In order to prevent the in&#45;<lb/>terference of shortsighted&#44; ignorant<lb/> and prejudiced parties to disturb us<lb/> in our movement&#44; with the display<lb/> that we are going to burden our<lb/> charities with an Immigration<lb/> and Labor Society&#44; I found it<lb/> necessary to publish a part<lb/> of my yesterday&#91;&#39;&#93;s communic&#45; <lb/>ation to Geo L. Lyon Esq. Enclosed<lb/> please find a cutting of today&#91;&#39;&#93;s<lb/> Public Ledger.<lb/></p>
            <p>Anyhow I intend to raise<lb/> some money after we will be<lb/> organized &#40;from such parties<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>who never contributed a cent<lb/> to the charities&#41; and I can  assure<lb/> you on the contrary when<lb/> we will have everything in<lb/> running order that we will<lb/> do with our labor bureau<lb/> great assistance to the U.H.C.<lb/> by getting employment for the<lb/> poor and working able of this <lb/> city&#91;.&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>Very resply<lb/>
                J Judelsohn<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Public<lb/> Ledger<lb/>
                Sept<lb/>
                25&#47;84<lb/></p>
                
            <p><emph rend="italics">Concerning the Movement to Organize a<lb/> Jewish Immigration Society</emph>.&#45;&#45; Mr. J. Ju&#45;<lb/>delsohn&#44; at whose instance the recent meet&#45;<lb/>ing to consider the project of organizing a<lb/> permanent Jewish Immigration Society in<lb/> this city was held&#44; has written to Mr. Geo. L. Lyon&#44; Hon. Secretary of the Jews&#39; Emi&#45;<lb/>gration Society of London&#44; England&#44; giving<lb/> an account of the progress of the movement<lb/> here. He says&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>&#34;I am happy to state that the movement of<lb/> the emigration affair is at present very<lb/> strong in this city. But I am afraid that if <lb/> the Hamburg Committee will continue<lb/> sending hither companies of emigrants be&#45;<lb/> fore a regular organization to receive them<lb/> and to provide work for them be effected&#44;<lb/> the kindly sentiments of our good men will<lb/> be used up before any permanent good will<lb/> be accomplished. It would&#44; therefore&#44; be<lb/> advisable to stop sending emigrants to this<lb/> port for a few months.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#34; I am persuaded&#44;&#34; Mr. Judelsohn goes<lb/> on to say&#44; &#34;that it will take but a very short<lb/> time until our organization will be perfected<lb/> in this city&#44; to receive and provide work for<lb/> our unfortunate brethren&#44; the emigrants.<lb/> Mr. Simon Muhr has already sent out an ap&#45;<lb/>peal to the Rabbis of this city&#44; that they<lb/> should with their influence lend assistance<lb/> to the good cause. So also did Mr. Moses A.<lb/> Dropsie&#44; as well as Mr. Alfred T. Jones&#44; the editor of the <emph rend="italics">Jewish Record</emph>&#44; promise to do all&#44; that is in their power to establish an organi&#45;<lb/>zation with employment bureaus for our im&#45;<lb/>migrants.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#34;According to your letter of the 20<hi rend="sup">th</hi> ult. I <lb/> promised those gentlemen that they would<lb/> get means to manage it from your Society&#44; <lb/>because we cannot expect to get means here<lb/> at the beginning. The Jews of this city<lb/> have to support the Jewish Hospital&#44; Jewish<lb/> Foster Home&#44; Jewish Education Society&#44;<lb/> Young Men&#39;s Hebrew Association&#44; the<lb/> United Hebrew Charities of Philadelphia&#44; <lb/>and a few more kindred institutions&#44; and<lb/> we cannot expect to get means in this city to<lb/> manage the Emigration Society with the<lb/> Employment Bureau.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#34;Therefore please set yourself at corres&#45;<lb/>pondence after receiving this letter with<lb/> Simon Muhr&#44; Esq.&#44; 635 Chestnut <sic>street</sic>&#44; and<lb/> Moses A. Dropsie&#44; Esq.&#44; 29 South Sixth<lb/> <sic>street</sic>&#44; Philadelphia&#44; and explain that you<lb/> are willing to co&#45;operate with them&#44; and that<lb/> you are responsible for the expense which<lb/> they have advanced from the funds of the<lb/> Branch of the Alliance Israelite Universelle&#44;<lb/> as Mr. Dropsie is the President&#44; and Mr.<lb/> Muhr the Treasurer of that Society.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#34;In the meantime&#44; I would beg you to<lb/> communicate with the Committee of Ham&#45;<lb/>burg telling them to send no emigrants to<lb/> this port until a regular organization be es&#45;<lb/> tablished here.&#34;<lb/></p>
        </body>
